Apr 21 2008 	good little hotel	I've been using the Boulevard hotel 1-2 times a year since 2004. I usually fly to London for a long weekend for some shopping and cultural pleasures, travelling either alone or with my hubby. I have always been content with the price/quality ratio, and this trip was no exception. The Boulevard is a small, modern hotel, and is, like most of small hotels in London, situated in an old townhouse. The rooms are tiny, but clean and functional with Scandinavian style modern decor: light wood, laminate floors, flat screen tv etc. The bed in double rooms is a queen-size one, and in single rooms there's a single bed. The beds are comfy and the bedlinen has always been immaculately clean. There is a small cupboard/dressing table unit (with a hairdryer) in each room, but that's about it regarding the storage space. If you have a lot of luggage, you might want to consider one of the bigger double rooms. There are coffee/tea -making facilities in each room. I've usually had a room at the back where it's quieter, but had no trouble sleeping in a room facing the street. But if you are a very light sleeper, bring earplugs. There is also some noise from the corridor, but only occasionally. (Having said that, during my last visit the floorboards in the room above creaked when the occupant walked there, but it was not that bad).The bathrooms are really tiny, but clean and feature everything needed. The showers have good water pressure and enough hot water. There are soap/shower gel dispensers and towels are changed daily.During the last year or so, the hotel's owner has apparently changed. The rooms have also had a small facelift (new curtains etc), and the prices have gone up slightly. Previously, the hotel reception area acted also as the breakfast area (breakfast consisted of cereal, toast, coffee/tea, juice), but in March 2008 the reception area was under renovation and we got breakfast coupons for the cafe next door instead.In most cases, the hotel staff has been friendly and informative, and they have let me store my bags for the day at the reception after the check-out if I've had an evening flight home.The Paddington area is filled with restaurants &amp; pubs and the transportation links both to Heathrow &amp; city centre are excellent: Paddington rail station and several tube lines within 5 mins walk. There is also a handy bus connection, line 23, that runs to Liverpool Station 24/7 for easy access to the Stansted Exporess and Stansted airport. The bus stops right in front of the hotel.This hotel is perfect for someone that is looking for a comfy place to sleep in, but does not want much more from the hotel. The rooms are suitable for max. 2 people with not that much luggage. There's no lift at the hotel, so be prepared to carry your own luggage up the stairs. I recommend this hotel for independent travellers, tourists and other people who are looking for a clean, reasonably-priced place to stay.To sum it up: nice little hotel with small but clean rooms. Good connections. Know what to expect, and you'll like it.	
