Mar 8 2007 	Basic clean friendly and reasonably priced. What's not to like?	I've been staying at the Boulevard Hotel 3 nights a week since November 2006, when my previous &quot;digs&quot; (The London House in Craven Hill) went into administration, closed down and kicked me out at a weeks notice.The Boulevard is quite small, with fairly limited facilities. It's basically a bed and breakfast establishment with all the rooms en-suite. The rooms tend to be on the small side as others have noticed, but I haven't had any real problems despite being a 16 stone, 6-foot-2 male. The decor is quite plain and restful - blond wood, laminate floors, cream walls. I think the building was refurbished a few years ago and it's definitely starting to show wear and tear, but I'm told that it has recently changed hands and the new owners are in the process of organising another refurb.I basically use it as a place to sleep when I'm in London for work, leaving after breakfast at about 9:30 am and usually not returning until after 10 pm. There's no lift and the stairs are quite narrow, so it's just as well I only have a small wheely case and a backpack - anyone with two weeks' luggage in a big case could have a difficult time getting to a room on the third floor. Also, the storage facilities in the rooms aren't huge - the wardrobes in particular are very small, so you might be living out of a suitcase for the duration. Again, not a problem for me with minimal luggage.Things I like: comfortable beds, controllable heating (and air con which I haven't had to use yet), excellent showers (a really nice, high pressure deluge!), really friendly and helpful staff, excellent location (4 minutes' walk from Paddington station), cleanliness (excellent), price (reasonable). Reception is open 24 hours a day which is great, since I usually check in quite late on my arrival night. Breakfast is a bit limited (white toast with butter and a selection of jams, croissants, cornflakes, orange juice with your choice of tea, coffee etc.) but they did have an arrangement with a small restaurant next door which does a &quot;full english&quot; for a small extra fee. Not sure if this is still going, however. To be honest, being picky I tend to take my own tea bags, granary bread and marmalade down with me and the staff toast the bread for me and so forth. Little things matter when you spend half your life away from home. :)Things I don't like: the rooms at the front of the hotel overlook a bus stop and have single glazed sash windows. This means that you can hear buses going past until very late at night, so for light sleepers it might be better to ask for a room at the back of the building. There is no internet access in the building - I have asked, and it's on the list of things to be done, but I get the impression it's quite a long way down the list. I find this annoying since I work in IT and I'm used to hot and cold running net access at all times, but then that might just be me. The fact that the floors are all laminate means an inconsiderate guest on the floor above can really spoil your evening by coming in late at night and banging around, but unfortunately there's not a lot one can do about it - luck of the draw. The breakfast room (which is basically the entrance foyer) is quite small (about 7 tables each seating 2-3 people) and at certain times can be completely full so you'll have to wait to sit down for breakfast - although in fairness this has only happened to me twice in 3 months. The bathrooms (really shower rooms) in each room are very small and I sometimes find it difficult to get close enough to the sink when shaving, resulting in water all over the bathroom floor.Things to avoid: a couple of the rooms are subject to a weird reverberating noise which sounds like an electric motor running in the next room for about 30 seconds every few minutes. This kept me awake and I've since asked never to be put in those rooms again!So, in summary, a reasonably priced, clean but basic bed and breakfast with great staff and a great location. A few niggles, but in general it's a nice little place to stay.	
